            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How to convert Hz to MHz</h2>
              <p>
                Hertz (Hz) and Megahertz (MHz) are both units of frequency.
                Hertz counts cycles per second, while Megahertz is a million
                cycles per second.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Conversion formulas</p>
                <p class="mb-1">From Hertz to Megahertz:</p>
                <p class="mb-2">
                  \[ \text{MHz} = \frac{\text{Hz}}{1{,}000{,}000} \]
                </p>
                <p class="mb-1">From Megahertz to Hertz:</p>
                <p>\[ \text{Hz} = \text{MHz} \times 1{,}000{,}000 \]</p>
              </div>

              <h3>Step-by-step example</h3>
              <p><strong>Example 1:</strong> Convert 5,000,000 Hz to MHz.</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Write the formula: \(\text{MHz} = \text{Hz} \div
                  1{,}000{,}000\)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Substitute the value: \(\text{MHz} = 5{,}000{,}000 \div
                  1{,}000{,}000\)
                </li>
                <li>Compute: \(\text{MHz} = 5\)</li>
              </ol>
              <p>So, <strong>5,000,000 Hz = 5 MHz</strong>.</p>

              <p><strong>Example 2:</strong> Convert 2.4 MHz to Hz.</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Use the reverse formula: \(\text{Hz} = \text{MHz} \times
                  1{,}000{,}000\)
                </li>
                <li>Substitute: \(\text{Hz} = 2.4 \times 1{,}000{,}000\)</li>
                <li>Compute: \(\text{Hz} = 2{,}400{,}000\)</li>
              </ol>
              <p>So, <strong>2.4 MHz = 2,400,000 Hz</strong>.</p>

              <h3>Scientific notation</h3>
              <p>
                For very large or very small frequencies, scientific notation is
                convenient:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>1 MHz = \(1 \times 10^{6}\) Hz</li>
                <li>100 MHz = \(1 \times 10^{8}\) Hz</li>
                <li>2.4 GHz = \(2.4 \times 10^{9}\) Hz = 2,400 MHz</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This converter accepts inputs like <code>3e8</code>,
                <code>4.5E6</code>, or <code>1.2e7</code> directly.
              </p>

              <h2>Common Hz to MHz conversions</h2>
              <div class="overflow-x-auto">
                <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
                  <thead class="bg-gray-50">
                    <tr>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 border-b text-left">Hertz (Hz)</th>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 border-b text-left">
                        Megahertz (MHz)
                      </th>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 border-b text-left">Notes</th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
