                      <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">VHF range</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">2,400,000,000 Hz</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">2400 MHz</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">2.4 GHz Wi‑Fi band</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">3,200,000,000 Hz</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">3200 MHz</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-1 border-b">3.2 GHz CPU clock</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>

              <h2>Hz vs kHz vs MHz vs GHz</h2>
              <p>All of these are powers-of-ten multiples of Hertz:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>1 kHz = \(10^3\) Hz = 1,000 Hz</li>
                <li>1 MHz = \(10^6\) Hz = 1,000,000 Hz</li>
                <li>1 GHz = \(10^9\) Hz = 1,000,000,000 Hz</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Moving one step up (Hz → kHz → MHz → GHz) divides by 1,000 each
                time. Moving one step down multiplies by 1,000.
              </p>

              <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>How do you convert Hz to MHz?</h3>
              <p>
                Divide the Hertz value by 1,000,000. For example, 20,000,000 Hz
                ÷ 1,000,000 = 20 MHz. The calculator does this automatically as
                you type.
              </p>

              <h3>How many Hz are in 1 MHz?</h3>
              <p>
                Exactly 1,000,000 Hz. That’s why MHz is convenient for radio,
                electronics, and CPU clock speeds: it avoids writing long
                strings of zeros.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I convert MHz back to Hz?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Enter a value in the MHz field and the Hz field updates
                instantly using \(\text{Hz} = \text{MHz} \times 1{,}000{,}000\).
              </p>

              <h3>Does rounding matter?</h3>
              <p>
                For most practical uses (electronics, RF, networking), rounding
                to 3–6 decimal places in MHz is more than enough. This tool
                keeps full internal precision and only rounds the displayed
                value.
              </p>
